    <p class="teaser">The right policies and financial structures will accelerate the adoption of green technologies.</p>
  </div>      </div>
      </div>
</div>

<div class="container" id="content-column-2">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-10 col-sm-offset-1 col-lg-8 col-lg-offset-2">
              <h2>Optimistic outlook</h2>
      
      <p>Through collaborations at Stanford and with colleagues worldwide – as well as through the many energy companies founded by Stanford faculty – many research areas once considered high-risk and experimental are starting to pay off.</p>
<aside class="pull-right pull-right-wide pushdown card story-supplement">
<div class="story-supplement-content">
<h2>Transferring innovation</h2>
<p>Convincing energy companies to invest in new technologies can be a major hurdle for innovators. To address the problem, Stanford’s <a href="/http://news.stanford.edu/2017/06/06/innovation-transfer-program-helps-students/">TomKat Center for Sustainable Energy</a> created the Innovation Transfer Program, which helps students turn novel energy concepts into viable commercial products.</p>
<p>“We want to get some of the great ideas being worked on at Stanford out beyond the university walls,” said&nbsp;<a href="/https://profiles.stanford.edu/stacey-bent">Stacey Bent</a>, a professor of chemical engineering and director of the TomKat Center. “We provide a little extra time, a little bit of money and a lot of mentorship to bridge the gap between research and commercialization.”</p>
</div>
</aside>
<p>For example, clean-energy technologies – especially solar and wind power – have experienced explosive growth worldwide as prices have plummeted in recent years.</p>
<p>In 1975, it cost $101 to generate a single watt of electricity from a silicon solar panel. By 2016, the <a href="/http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy17osti/68425.pdf">price</a> had dropped as low as 35¢ per watt. The U.S. solar industry, virtually nonexistent 15 years ago, is now valued at about $30 billion and employs some 260,000 Americans. And green cars are following a similar path. Electric cars are expected to outsell their gas-fueled counterparts in some parts of the world within the next two decades.</p>
<p>For Mike McGehee, whose research trajectory changed so dramatically with GCEP funding, the trend is positive.</p>
<p>“I take the long view,” he said. “Climate change is not going away. Demand for energy globally is going up. If there are improvements in grid-scale energy storage, and if electric vehicles become significantly more popular, we could have massive growth in the solar industry for decades.”</p>
<aside class="align-center center-block pushdown card story-supplement">
<div class="story-supplement-content">
<div class="pull-left pull-left-portrait"><a href="/https://energy.stanford.edu/research/research-areas"><img class=" wp-image-16628 img-responsive" alt="" srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/25105901/PIEHexStickerV3-final2-555x669.png 555w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/25105901/PIEHexStickerV3-final2.png 741w" sizes="(max-width: 132px) 100vw, 132px" src="/https://s3-us-west-1.amazonaws.com/stanford.ucomm.newsms.media/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/25105901/PIEHexStickerV3-final2-555x669.png"></a></div>
<p><a href="/https://energy.stanford.edu/research/research-areas">Explore all energy research and faculty at Stanford.</a></p>
</div>
</aside>
    </div> <!-- /columns -->
